Predicted vs. True Time Series

Sections

  • Analysis Summary

  • Residuals by Timepoint Position

  • Single plot of ALL Residuals by Difficulty Level

Overview

This page contains summary plots of predicted vs. true timeseries for each run. R2 plots across sessions are first shown for reference. Next, average residuals are shown for each 30-timepoint (45s -- 30s task, 15s rest) block. All data within run (263 TRs) were used to fit the model. Predicted timeseries are shown for each run.

The predicted timeseries uses a design matrix that was convolved with the hrf, while true values are fit to scaled timeseries (median of motor region voxels).

Green color bars in timeseries plots represent when the task came. Black dots show average residuals for each 45s block (30s task, 15s rest).

(go back to top)

Updates

  • 8/4/25: Model has been rerun without scaling the timeseries to check if scaling was an issue before.

Analysis Summary

(go back to top)

Problem: Previously the predictions in cross-validated ridge regression models were systematically different. It seemed like maybe the sessions with higher difficulties were not predicted well, but there were not clear patterns present in the data as far as we could tell.

Potential Explanations:

  • Differences in data quality across sessions/runs
  • Difficulty level is not captured by the model
    • We only captured differences in BOLD signal due to difficulty level based on the assumption that differences could only be due to greater number of stimuli
    • Other sources of neural amplitude differences due to difficulty level would not be captured by the model
  • The feature space is not specified well in some other way (e.g., it's not flexible enough)

So far we tested:

  • Do the within-run models fit the data well?
    • R² scores across sessions are shown for reference.
    • Within-run Ridge regression models were run and the regularization parameter associated with the highest R-squared was chosen.
  • Does the model fit change across blocks within a run, regardless of difficulty?
    • Residuals by timepoint position are shown for each session/run.
    • Residuals were averaged across each 45s/30 TR block (30s task, 15s rest) for each session/run.
  • Does the model appear to fit the data well?
    • Session/Run Plots are shown for each session/run.
    • TBD
  • Is the neural activation magnitude varying by difficulty?
    • Residuals by difficulty level are shown for each session/run.
    • Residuals were averaged across each 45s/30 TR block within-run and then plotted against difficulty level.
    • There doesn't appear to be a consistent trend pattern, but we could try splitting the features up by difficulty level regardless to see if there's model improvement.
